From Windows XP to Linux Mint

Microsoft has cut security updates for all Windows XP computers since April 8, 2014. This means that your computer can be put at risk to be attacked by anything on the Internet -- viruses, hackers, basically anything bad on the Internet.

Microsoft has recommended that you upgrade to Windows 7 or buy a new computer. However, if your old computer cannot support Windows 7 or if you don't want to buy a new computer, you're not out of luck either. By replacing Windows XP with an XP-themed version of Linux Mint, you're guaranteed security updates until at least 2020. The best part of all this is that you'll still have the familiar feel and features of Windows XP, all with barely any lag on even the oldest computers.

What you'll need

  • 2 USB flash drives, 4GB or higher
  • A Windows XP computer
  • A browser (Internet Explorer, Google Chrome, or Firefox)
  • An Internet connection

What we'll be doing

We will be replacing Windows XP with an XP-themed version of Linux Mint.

Warning: Back up all your data before starting. All data will be gone after you finish.

Step 1 - Preparation

  • Download Linux Mint
  • Download Rufus
  • USB Flash Drives
<
>
  1. Go to the Linux Mint download page here.
  2. Scroll down to "MATE" and click on the "32-bit" option.
  3. In the "Download mirrors" section, click on the link next to "World"
  4. A file will download. Save the file to your computer.
  5. As you wait for the download to complete, move on to the next section.
  1. Go to the Rufus download page here.
  2. Scroll down to the "Download" section.
  3. Click on "Rufus x.xx Portable"
  4. A file will download. Save the file to your computer.
  5. As you wait for the download to complete, move on to the next section.
  1. Make sure you have 2 new USB flash drives and that it is 4GB or higher
  2. Plug one of them into the computer
  3. Back up all your important files onto that flash drive. Everything else on your computer will be wiped clean.
  4. When you're done, unplug that flash drive, and any other USB flash drives you have (if applicable) and put them off to the side.
  5. Plug in your 2nd new USB flash drive into the computer.

Step 2 - Setting Up

  • Using Rufus
  • Restart Computer
  • Installing Linux Mint
<
>
  1. Back in your browser, Rufus should have finished downloading. Open the file.
  2. Near the lower right corner, next to "ISO Image", click on the disk icon.
  3. Find the Linux Mint file you downloaded in your computer, and double-click on it.
  4. Press "Start" on the lower right corner.
  5. Wait for the process to complete. Then follow on-screen instructions.

Note: Please load this website on another device (such as a phone), or print out the following instructions. Your computer will need to shut down after this.
  1. Shut down your computer, but keep the USB flash drive plugged in.
  2. Immediately after turning your computer back on, keep pressing the F12 key on your keyboard
       (different computers may vary: if it doesn't work, try F2 or F10) 
  3. A numbered list should show up. Use the arrow keys to select the "USB flash drive" option, then press Enter.
  4. Wait for everything to load. It should take 1-5 minutes.
  5. After it is done loading, a desktop should appear. Move on to the next section.
  1. A basic desktop should appear. On the left, double-click on "Install Linux Mint".
  2. Follow on-screen instructions to install Linux Mint.
  3. When asked, choose to completely erase Windows XP and replace it with Linux Mint.
  4. Wait for the installation to complete. Follow on-screen instructions.

Step 3 - Finishing Up

  • Downloading Theme
  • Setting Up Theme
  • Google Chrome
<
>
  1. Open Firefox Web Browser from the desktop.
  2. Click here to download the Windows XP Theme (by winxp4life.tk)
  3. Save the file to your computer.
  4. When the file finishes downloading, open the file.
  5. Find the "Extract" button on the top row of buttons. Where the files are extracted to does not matter -- just extract the files.
  6. When the files finish extracting, click "Show the files".
  7. Double-click "install.sh" and follow on-screen instructions.
  1. On the desktop, right click and click "Change Desktop Background"
  2. Click on the "Themes" tab in the top left corner.
  3. Scroll down to the "Luna" theme and click once.
  4. Press "Close" to save your settings.

If you would like, you can also change the background by going back to the "Backgrounds" tab and changing the background.
Optional: This is a one-time setup of Google Chrome. This is not required, but is recommended.
  1. Press the following keyboard shortcut: Ctrl+Alt+T
  2. A white box labeled "Terminal" should appear.
  3. Next, type in the following and press Enter:

    sudo apt-get update

  4. Wait for everything to stop. Next, type in the following and press Enter:

    sudo apt-get install chromium-browser

  5. Wait for everything to stop. You will be prompted to install Google Chrome. Type "Y" and press Enter to continue.
  6. Wait for everything to stop. You may now close the Terminal.

Usage Tutorial

Everything else from here on out will be more or less the same as with Windows XP. To access Google Chrome, you can find a desktop shortcut. From browsing the web to downloading files, everything can be taken care of.

You can now move your files in your 1st USB flash drive back onto your new updated computer.

Here are the minor differences between Windows XP and your new Linux Mint computer. They look and work almost exactly the same. The transition will be easy and seamless.

  • Windows Update -> Software Updater
  • Microsoft Word 2003/2007 -> LibreOffice
  • Windows Media Player -> VLC Media Player
  • Welcome
  • Home
  • Windows
  • Android
